fields.title: Predicting Mobility Behaviour
fields.description: Developed 4 random forest models to predict mode splits based on urban form changes for different commuting modes (walking, cycling, driving and public transit). The models were trained using Journey to Work census data at the Dissemination Area level sourced from Statistics Canada as dependent variables, and urban form data sourced from BC Assessment, Statistics Canada and OpenStreetMap as explanatory variables.

fields.title: Identifying Neighbourhood Clusters
fields.description: Using spatial analysis to identify commercial neighbourhood clusters across Vancouver. The project is being developed for a research project with the elementslab in collaboration with the City of Vancouver.

fields.title: Modelling Walking Patterns
fields.description: Using spatial analysis (space syntax) to model walkability patterns at the Olympic Village in Vancouver, BC. Conference paper.

fields.title: Urban Form and Livability Indicators
fields.description: Journal article

fields.title: Typological Urban Design Generator
fields.description: This personal project is an urban development generator. It uses a typological approach to generate urban designs configurations across multiple scales based on parameters of 10 development types: Single-Unit Detached, Bungalow Court, Duplexes, Townhouse, Live/Work, Mini Mid-Rise, Courtyard, Podium Tower, Cascading Tower and Detached Tower. An integrated model estimates a rough (yet customizable) feasibility study. The frontend was developed using Dash-Deck and the whole project is written in Python.

fields.title: Procedural Urban Design Generator
fields.description: Procedural modelling generator for urban design using site curve, water flow lines and neighbourhood centers as inputs.

fields.title: Cellular Automata Urban Design Generator
fields.description: Generative urban design "sandbox" approach based on the definition of "tile cells". 9 urban form neighborhood (150x150m) types were identified using a cluster algorithm with parcels, buildings, vegetation and street network data. The project is being developed for a research project with the elementslab in collaboration with the City of Vancouver.

fields.title: Deep Learning Building Footprint Generator
fields.description: In this simple project I trained and tested the TensorFlow pix2pix model to generate building footprints based on parcel boundaries. Although results were satisfactory, more training epochs should improve the realism of the outputs. For future research, integrating more data such as maximum height and floor space ratio will be useful. The code is available in GitHub.

fields.title: Ribeira's Eyes Historic District Masterplan
fields.description:
The competition asked for ideas in order to revitalize the old central neighbourhood of Ribeira in the coastal city of Natal regarding social, economic and environmental sustainability. Our winning proposal derives from the idea that the best solution to urban issues can only be found by engaging stakeholders in an attempt to find a middle ground among all of the interests surrounding the place. Buildings and public spaces designed for a new Ribeira would be placed in a mobile app so that community, regulators and developers could decide decentrally and through collective financing, the most desired projects throughout the neighborhood.

I used parametric modelling tools to optimize spatial density and diversity while keeping the views of the surroundings and minimizing shadows on buildings and parks. Among the solutions we proposed a waterfront deck connecting public spaces to the Potengi river along with boat marines and a natural habitat park at one end of the deck; restoration of abandoned heritage buildings into mixed-use enterprises stimulated by tax and regulation incentives; social and affordable mixed-use housing at densifiable districts; a mixed public market and car parking building; sustainable efficient urban furniture and new cyclepaths and linear parks interconnecting all of the solutions.

The work was developed in four main phases: one early phase for designing a panel of ideas from june to august, a second phase with three more detailed panels from august to october, a third phase with a presentation of the best three projects at the IDB headquarters in Washington, D.C. in november and a fourth phase of summarizing the ideas in our winning proposal into a 150 pages book Ribeira’s Eyes Masterplan from mar/2018 to mar/2019.

fields.title: Paranoa Lake Masterplan
fields.description:
This planning competition asked us to design a Masterplan for the surroundings of the Paranoá Lake in the city of Brasília. I used Grasshopper to model all urban blocks and simulate pedestrian paths in order to scale up and facilitate the design of multiple areas at the same time. Our plan had four main axis of intervention:

(1) Mobility: one of the driving forces of the intervention was an Integrated Mobility Plan (intermodality of the terminals with existing modes of transportation, introduction of light rail transport and water ferries and extension of the cyclable network). Given the proposed connectivity and its consequent wide access, it guarantees the right to the city, bringing the lake back to the daily life of the city and its citizens. 

(2) Urban vitality: Bridging the urban fabric and encouraging the occupation of existing gaps between the original Pilot Plan and the Paranoá Lake is an effective way to increase the movement of pedestrians along the waterfront. We propose a mixed use occupation with financial incentives to sustainable practices such as rainwater harvesting, electric power production and green areas increase.

(3) Sport and Laisure: Many spaces suitable for bathing and integration with residential areas reinforce the potential of this stretch of the north lake to receive a large Linear Park to support the practicy of daily sports and other leisure activities. 

(4) Ecotourism: Wildlife preservation areas and ecological parks receive a trail treatment as a means of attracting ecotourism and qualifying access to the lake.

fields.title: Sol Nascente Social Housing
fields.description:
9th place out of 89 submissions

A successful mixed-use project should design open spaces with great urban vitality through forms that allows a frequent use of public space by pedestrians. We took advantage from the sites’ configuration for the Sol Nascente mixed-use project and proposes to create pedestrian flows through the sites.

(1) The project developed by the for sets B1 and B2 will be replicated for another five blocks, each with different topographic differences. A thickened mono-block makes implantation difficult of the building, leaving the ground floors with high ceiling height and resorting to the movements of considerable land. Thus we divide the sets into two blocks in order to create a smooth transition from public to private spaces. Around the land, we propose the growth of native vegetation.

(2) The drawing of volumes with recesses and patios open and covered, brings lightness and dynamism to the built mass, maintaining continue mobility. Those full and empty were articulated considering privacy and sociability at the same time, reinforcing individual and community values by creating visible public spaces and hidden private rooms.

(3) The configuration of the “U” blocks maintains the continuity of facades at the same time it provides a space shared by residents on the pavement ground floor. Movement among the units were designed to provide more natural lighting and ventilation, avoiding a sense of enclosure.

(4) All single-storey facades facing main streets were intended for commercial use. The project also encompasses a community hall intended for residents. A stair-ramp follows the topographic unevenness of the street creating accessible places for everyone without compromising the connection of the  ground level commerces.

fields.title: Philosophy Doctor
fields.description:
Affordable Accessibility: Using Generative Methods to Optimize Urban Design for Active Accessibility and Rental Housing Affordability

ANALYTICAL PROBLEM-SOLVING
Uncovered problems of urban affordability, accessibility and complexity that can be potentially attenuated by using computational design to optimize urban policy-making.

GENERATIVE DESIGN
Performed a deep literature review on the subject. Developed tests to generate architectural forms using conditional Generative Adversarial Networks with TensorFlow and procedural modelling techniques with GeoPandas.

DATA ACQUISITION + MANAGEMENT
Scraped around 272,000 data points from Craigslist to a GeoPackage database. Scraped fine-grained census data for Metro Vancouver. Extracted cross-scale urban form indicators for each census Dissemination Area in Metro Vancouver using network analysis.

fields.title: Lead Urban Designer
fields.description:
MASTERPLAN DEVELOPMENT
Led the design of the 150-page Ribeira’s Eyes Masterplan for the re-development of a historic district in Natal, Brazil as a result of winning the UrbanLab competition in 2017. Developed occupation plans, urban policies and financial feasibility studies with city planners and community members.

COLLABORATIVE URBAN DESIGN
Collaborated with a team of 3 planners from the City of Natal, 1 planner from the Inter-American Development Bank.

GENERATIVE DESIGN
Developed a generative model in Grasshopper (cellular automata) using Voronoi grids to maximize density, sunlight exposure and green spaces.

DATA ACQUISITION + MANAGEMENT
Constructed a geospatial database at the neighborhood scale to manage the design of urban form guidelines, land use control, mobility networks, rainwater drainage systems and real estate development feasibility.

3D MODELLING
Developed 3D models in Rhino using Grasshopper to link geospatial data.

VISUAL COMMUNICATION
Produced 14 maps, 16 renderings and 13 diagrams using QGIS, Rhino, SketchUp and Illustrator.
